  <Fragment slot="methodology">
    <section>
      <h2 id="how-we-evaluate">How we evaluate</h2>
      <p>For this update, we compared each kettle against five practical decision factors: stream control, temperature behavior, ergonomics, capacity fit, and value versus feature set. We also reviewed how each model supports real home workflows, including single-cup weekday brews, two-cup back-to-back sessions, and slower weekend routines where stability matters more than speed.</p>
      <p><strong>Stream control</strong> was weighted first. In pour over coffee, your kettle is the steering wheel for extraction. A stable, predictable stream helps you manage bloom agitation and pulse timing without over-disturbing the bed. Kettles that feel jumpy near the end of a pour can make good recipes feel inconsistent even when grind and dose are solid.</p>
      <p><strong>Temperature behavior</strong> came next. Electric models were evaluated on ease of setting targets, hold-temperature behavior, and recovery between brews. Stovetop models were assessed on control feel and predictability when paired with a basic heating routine. The point is not gadget complexity — it is whether you can repeat your chosen recipe with low friction.</p>
      <p><strong>Ergonomics and balance</strong> were reviewed from a daily-use perspective: handle comfort, wrist stability during slow circles, and confidence when the kettle is partially filled. A kettle can have good specs and still be tiring to use if its balance is awkward mid-pour. That matters over hundreds of brews.</p>
      <p><strong>Capacity fit</strong> focused on real households. Many brewers overbuy capacity, then end up with a kettle that feels heavier and less precise than necessary. For most people, 0.8L to 1.0L is the best compromise between practical volume and pour control. Larger sizes make sense only if you consistently brew multiple cups per cycle.</p>
      <p><strong>Value</strong> compared what you actually gain at each price tier. Budget picks were rewarded for covering core brew needs without major compromise. Premium picks had to justify extra spend through meaningful workflow advantages, not cosmetic upgrades alone. This keeps recommendations useful for both first-time buyers and experienced brewers upgrading one part of a larger setup.</p>
      <p>If your kettle decision is tied to broader setup planning, pair this guide with our <a href="/posts/best-coffee-grinder-for-pour-over.html">best coffee grinder for pour over</a> roundup, then lock dose and yield with the <a href="/posts/coffee-brewing-ratio-guide.html">coffee brewing ratio guide</a>. For cleaner recipe consistency, a responsive scale also matters; see <a href="/posts/best-coffee-scale-for-espresso-and-pour-over.html">best coffee scale for espresso and pour over</a>.</p>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

