  <Fragment slot="extra-sections">
    <section>
      <h2>Electric vs stovetop gooseneck kettles</h2>
      <p>Both styles can produce excellent pour over coffee. The right choice depends on your routine, not internet debates. Electric kettles are best for consistency with lower effort: set target temperature, heat quickly, and repeat with less guesswork. Stovetop kettles are best for simplicity and long-term durability when you prefer manual control and fewer electronics.</p>
      <p>If you brew one cup before work and need fast recovery for a second cup, electric usually wins. Hold-temperature behavior helps avoid reboil cycles, and repeatable targets reduce recipe drift when you switch between coffees. In fast routines, these small convenience gains add up and often improve consistency by making the “correct process” easier to follow.</p>
      <p>Stovetop tends to win for buyers who value durability, straightforward maintenance, and lower complexity. With a stable routine, a stovetop kettle can be just as effective for extraction control. The key is consistency in your heat timing and pour pattern. If you already use a scale and timer reliably, manual workflows can be very repeatable.</p>
      <p>A practical rule: if convenience is your bottleneck, buy electric. If reliability and simplicity are your priorities, buy stovetop. Either way, your grinder quality and brew ratio discipline will still matter as much as kettle choice.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Common buying mistakes (and how to avoid them)</h2>
      <p><strong>Buying too much capacity.</strong> Bigger kettles can feel less agile and more fatiguing in delicate pours. Unless you regularly brew for several people at once, 0.8L to 1.0L is usually enough.</p>
      <p><strong>Chasing features instead of workflow fit.</strong> A long feature list does not guarantee better coffee. Prioritize controls you will actually use every week, not options you may never touch.</p>
      <p><strong>Ignoring water hardness and maintenance.</strong> Scale buildup affects heat behavior over time. Build descaling into your routine from day one so your kettle stays predictable.</p>
      <p><strong>Overspending before fixing bigger bottlenecks.</strong> If your grinder is inconsistent, kettle upgrades have reduced impact. Balance your budget across grinder, scale, and kettle to improve cups faster.</p>
      <p><strong>Choosing by aesthetics alone.</strong> Design matters, but control feel matters more. If possible, prioritize stream stability and handling confidence over visual style.</p>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="buying-guide">
    <BuyingGuideSection>
      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying guide: how to choose the right gooseneck kettle</h2>
      <p><strong>Step 1: define your brew rhythm.</strong> If you brew quickly before work or make multiple cups in sequence, an electric kettle with variable temperature and hold behavior is usually the better fit. If you prefer a slower manual routine and want fewer points of failure, a stovetop model can be the smarter long-term purchase.</p>
      <p><strong>Step 2: prioritize control over complexity.</strong> What matters most is how stable and comfortable the stream feels during real pours. Better control helps you execute bloom and pulse stages consistently, which improves extraction repeatability more than novelty features.</p>
      <p><strong>Step 3: match capacity to actual use.</strong> For most homes, 0.8L to 1.0L is the practical target. It covers one to two cups while keeping handling manageable. Move above that only if you regularly brew larger batches.</p>
      <p><strong>Step 4: consider maintenance realities.</strong> Electric models need occasional descaling and care around the base. Stovetop models are simpler mechanically but rely more on your heat management routine. Neither is wrong — just pick what you will maintain consistently.</p>
      <p><strong>Step 5: think in systems, not single products.</strong> A kettle helps, but cup quality comes from your full workflow: grinder consistency, scale accuracy, recipe tracking, and water choice. If you are still building your setup, continue with <a href="/posts/best-pour-over-coffee-maker.html">best pour over coffee maker</a> and <a href="/posts/best-coffee-grinder-for-pour-over.html">best coffee grinder for pour over</a> to close the loop.</p>
      <p><strong>Step 6: decide your upgrade horizon.</strong> If you expect to keep this kettle for many years, paying more for better ergonomics can make sense because comfort affects every brew. If you are still learning and may change methods soon, a value-first option is often smarter. Either way, define your goal before buying: reduce daily friction, increase recipe repeatability, or build a long-term ritual setup. That clarity will guide the right choice faster than brand hype.</p>
    </BuyingGuideSection>
  </Fragment>

